/> </mxCell> <mxCell id="yz2hSqQOMCemAEQzX0-a-250" value="<p style="font-size: 16px;"><font style="font-size: 16px;"><font style="font-size: 16px;">The aim of the Data Store is to provide a central vertex="1"> <mxGeometry x="-840" y="100" width="1680" height="70" as="geometry" /> </mxCell> <mxCell id="yz2hSqQOMCemAEQzX0-a-251" value="<p style="font-size: 16px;"><font style="font-size: 16px;">Just like a laboratory notebook on paper. All data stored in the Data Store is immutable and cannot be changed. So if a file or dataset changes, different versions should be saved and documented.<br> </font></p><p style="font-size: 16px;"><font style="font-size: 16px;">It is therefore advisable to consider within the division when the data is ready to be stored in the Data Store.&nbsp;</font></p><p style="font-size: 16px;"></p><div style="font-size: 16px;"><br></div>" style="text;html=1;align=left;verticalAlign=middle;whiteSpace=wrap;rounded=0;" parent="1" vertex="1"> <mxGeometry x="-840" y="170" width="1680" height="70" as="geometry" /> </mxCell> <mxCell id="yz2hSqQOMCemAEQzX0-a-252" value="<div style="font-size: 16px;"><font style="font-size: 16px;"><span style="background-color: initial;">The openBIS data structure is hierarchically organized in five (sub)folders called Space, Project, Collection, Object and Dataset. Folder names can be customized by users.</span><br></font></div><div style="font-size: 16px;"><span style="background-color: initial;"><font style="font-size: 16px;"><br></font></span></div><div style="font-size: 16px;"><span style="background-color: initial;"><font style="font-size: 16px;">To digitally represent an Object, a Space, Project and Collection need to be created first.</font></span></div><div style="font-size: 16px;"><br></div>" style="text;html=1;align=left;verticalAlign=middle;whiteSpace=wrap;rounded=0;" parent="1" vertex="1"> <mxGeometry x="2195.31" y="600" width="900" height="150" as="geometry" /> </mxCell> <mxCell id="yz2hSqQOMCemAEQzX0-a-253" value="<p style="font-size: 16px;"><font style="font-size: 16px;"><span style="background-color: initial;">To digitally represent research data in the Data Store. style="font-size: 16px;"><font style="font-size: 16px;"><font style="font-size: 16px;">The aim of the Data Store is to provide a central research data management (RDM)&nbsp;<span style="background-color: initial;">system</span><span style="background-color: initial;">&nbsp;in which all data (raw, processed, analyzed data, analysis code, etc.)&nbsp;</span></font><span 16px;"></p><div style="font-size: 16px;"><br></div>" style="text;html=1;align=left;verticalAlign=middle;whiteSpace=wrap;rounded=0;" parent="1" vertex="1"> <mxGeometry x="-850" y="350" width="1880" height="70" as="geometry" /> </mxCell> <mxCell id="0g92rMAiZ3Q5lK4Ixb0--2" value="<p style="font-size: 16px;"><font style="font-size: 16px;">Just like a laboratory notebook on paper. All data stored in the Data Store is immutable and cannot be changed. So if a file or dataset changes, different versions should be saved and documented.&nbsp; Hoewever a Dataset can be deleted and this will be saved in the "history".<br> </font></p><p style="font-size: 16px;"><font style="font-size: 16px;">It is therefore advisable to consider within the division when the data is ready to be stored in the Data Store.&nbsp;</font></p><p style="font-size: 16px;"></p><div style="font-size: 16px;"><br></div>" style="text;html=1;align=left;verticalAlign=middle;whiteSpace=wrap;rounded=0;" parent="1" vertex="1"> <mxGeometry x="-850" y="430" width="1880" height="90" as="geometry" /> </mxCell> <mxCell id="0g92rMAiZ3Q5lK4Ixb0--3" value="<p style="font-size: 16px;"><font style="font-size: 16px;"><span style="background-color: initial;">To digitally represent research data in the Data Store. We first need to create a Data model or visual representation of data and its relationships in the system. The data model</span><span style="background-color: initial;">&nbsp;is the basis for effective data management, analysis and collaboration within a research team. Therefore, the DSSt should lead the design of the data model and coordinate feedback rounds with the team or at least two or three colleagues from their division.&nbsp;</span></font></p><p style="font-size: 16px;"><font style="font-size: 16px;" face="Helvetica">This template is a conceptual schema with&nbsp; a conscise description of the data requirements based on a research workflow, definition of the Entity Types and relationships. The guideline aims to guide DSSt to model data for its digital representation in the BAM Data Store system.</font></p><p></p>" style="text;html=1;align=left;verticalAlign=middle;whiteSpace=wrap;rounded=0;" parent="1" vertex="1"> <mxGeometry x="-850" y="510" width="1880" height="130" as="geometry" /> </mxCell> <mxCell id="0g92rMAiZ3Q5lK4Ixb0--4" value="<p style="font-size: 16px;"><font style="font-size: 16px;"><font style="font-size: 16px;"><br></font></font></p><p style="font-size: 16px;"><font style="font-size: 16px;"><font style="font-size: 16px;">The openBIS data model contains:&nbsp;&nbsp;</font><span style="background-color: initial;"><b>1. Entities, 2. Properties, 3. Data Types, 4. Constraints and 5. Relations</b>. Data modelling is the process of creating a visual representation of data and its relationships in a system. Once components 1 to 5 are defined, the data is mapped in the&nbsp;<b>5. openBIS Data</b> Structure.</span></font></p><p style="font-size: 16px;"></p><p style="font-size: 16px;"></p><p style="font-size: 16px;"></p><ul style="font-size: 16px;"><li><span style="background-color: initial;"><font style="font-size: 16px;">Entities and Entity Types, Properties, Data Types and Constraints are defined by the DSSt and the team.</font></span></li></ul><p style="font-size: 16px;"></p><ul style="font-size: 16px;"><li><font style="font-size: 16px;">The relations are unidirectional parent-child relationships to link Objects to Objects and Datasets to Datasets. The DSSt and the team define what entities are connected.&nbsp;</font></li></ul><p style="font-size: 16px;"></p><p style="font-size: 16px;"></p><p style="font-size: 16px;"></p><p style="font-size: 16px;"></p><div style="font-size: 16px;"><br></div>" style="text;html=1;align=left;verticalAlign=middle;whiteSpace=wrap;rounded=0;" parent="1" vertex="1"> <mxGeometry x="-850" y="890" width="1880" height="140" as="geometry" /> </mxCell> <mxCell id="0g92rMAiZ3Q5lK4Ixb0--5" value="<div style="font-size: 16px;"><p style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt; margin-left: 0in; direction: ltr; unicode-bidi: embed; word-break: normal;"><font face="Helvetica">An Entity&nbsp;an item of the real world&nbsp;(tangible/non tangible) that&nbsp;is uniquely identified by&nbsp;Attributes.&nbsp;</font></p><p style="margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt; margin-left: 0in; direction: ltr; unicode-bidi: embed; word-break: normal;"><font face="Helvetica">Attributes are the <b style="">properties</b> that describe the Entity&nbsp;(Code,Name, etc.)</font></p></div>" style="text;html=1;align=left;verticalAlign=top;whiteSpace=wrap;rounded=0;" parent="1" vertex="1"> <mxGeometry x="-840" y="1179" width="800" height="72" as="geometry" /> </mxCell> <mxCell id="0g92rMAiZ3Q5lK4Ixb0--6" value="<h1 style="margin-top: 0px;">I.1 Entity&nbsp;</h1>" style="text;html=1;whiteSpace=wrap;overflow=hidden;rounded=0;" parent="1" vertex="1"> <mxGeometry x="-840" y="1137" width="800" height="42" as="geometry" /> </mxCell> <mxCell id="0g92rMAiZ3Q5lK4Ixb0--7" value="<h1 style="margin-top: 0px;">I.2 Entity Types</h1>" style="text;html=1;whiteSpace=wrap;overflow=hidden;rounded=0;" parent="1" vertex="1"> <mxGeometry y="1134" width="1040" height="50" as="geometry" /> </mxCell> <mxCell id="0g92rMAiZ3Q5lK4Ixb0--8" value="<p style="font-size: 16px;"><font style="font-size: 16px;"><font face="Helvetica">Entity Types are a collection&nbsp;of Entities with <b style="">similar </b><b style="">properties </b>(Chemical, Glassware, Experimental Step,<br>Instruments, etc). Entitiy Types are Objects in openBIS.&nbsp; Relevant Entity Types in openBIS are Collection, Object, Dataset or Property - Types.&nbsp; Entity Types together with Controlled Vocabularies conform the openBIS Masterdata.</font><br></font></p><p style="font-size: 16px;"><span style="font-size: 14px; font-family: &quot;BAM Klavika Light&quot;;"><br></span></p>" style="text;html=1;align=left;verticalAlign=bottom;whiteSpace=wrap;rounded=0;" parent="1" vertex="1"> <mxGeometry y="1176" width="1040" height="110" as="geometry" /> </mxCell> <mxCell id="0g92rMAiZ3Q5lK4Ixb0--9" value="<h1 style="margin-top: 0px;">I.3 Properties &amp; Data Types&nbsp;</h1>" style="text;html=1;whiteSpace=wrap;overflow=hidden;rounded=0;" parent="1" vertex="1"> <mxGeometry x="1179.85" y="1140" width="940.15" height="40" as="geometry" /> </mxCell> <mxCell id="0g92rMAiZ3Q5lK4Ixb0--10" value="<div style=""><div><font style="font-size: 16px;">Domain-specific master data must be defined by the data store stewards, but can only be imported (and edited) into the openBIS instance by instance administrators (data store team).</font></div><div><font size="3">Property restrictions are defined by the data type that is assigned to the property. For example, a property with the data type Controlled Vocabulary (CV) is restricted to the terms contained in the CV.</font><span style="font-size: medium; background-color: initial;">&nbsp;</span><font size="3">&nbsp;The type of restriction that can be applied to properties depends on their data type.</font></div></div><div style=""><font size="3">&nbsp;<span style="color: rgb(66, 66, 66); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);"><br></span></font></div><div style=""><span style="color: rgb(66, 66, 66); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);"><font size="3"><br></font></span></div><div style=""><span style="color: rgb(66, 66, 66); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);"><font size="3"><br></font></span></div><div style=""><span style="color: rgb(66, 66, 66); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);"><font size="3"><br></font></span></div><div style=""><span style="color: rgb(66, 66, 66); font-size: 16px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);"><br></span></div>" style="text;html=1;align=left;verticalAlign=top;whiteSpace=wrap;rounded=0;" parent="1" vertex="1"> <mxGeometry x="1175.1599999999999" y="1182" width="940" height="130" as="geometry" /> </mxCell> <mxCell id="0g92rMAiZ3Q5lK4Ixb0--11" value="I.4 Hierarchical openBIS Data Structure and relationships" style="text;strokeColor=none;fillColor=none;html=1;fontSize=24;fontStyle=1;verticalAlign=middle;align=left;" parent="1" vertex="1"> <mxGeometry x="2204" y="1137" width="866" height="30" as="geometry" /> </mxCell> <mxCell id="0g92rMAiZ3Q5lK4Ixb0--12" value="<div style="font-size: 16px;"><font style="font-size: 16px;"><span style="background-color: initial;">The openBIS data structure is hierarchically organized in five (sub)folders called Space, Project, Collection, Object and Dataset. It is encouraged to add items to the BAM Inventory which belong to BAM. This would improve findability of items and facilitate to all divisions the definition of&nbsp; metadata for items that belong to more than one division, for example generic instruments (Microsocopes, centrifutes, Mass spectrometers, etc.) and large devices (Scanners for nuclear magnetic resonace, etc.)&nbsp;</span></li><li style="forced-color-adjust: none;"><span style="font-size: 16px;">Default Spaces for both "privat and public" inventories are: "Equipment, Materials, Methods and Publications"</span></li><li style="forced-color-adjust: none;"><span style="font-size: 16px;">Default Spaces for Lab Notebook are set for every BAM member: X.Y_User&nbsp;</span><br></li><li style="forced-color-adjust: none;"><span style="font-size: 16px;">To have additional spaces for exaple to organize the Lab Notebook per Projects, please contact the Data Store team.</span></li></ul>" style="text;whiteSpace=wrap;html=1;" parent="1" vertex="1"> <mxGeometry x="7040" y="3256.5" width="1495" height="190" as="geometry" /> </mxCell> <mxCell id="0g92rMAiZ3Q5lK4Ixb0--244" value="Guideline to digitally represent research data in the BAM Data Store - openBIS RDM system<div><br></div>" style="text;strokeColor=none;fillColor=none;html=1;fontSize=24;fontStyle=1;verticalAlign=middle;align=left;" parent="1" vertex="1"> <mxGeometry x="-850" y="270" width="1880" height="70" as="geometry" /> </mxCell> <mxCell id="0g92rMAiZ3Q5lK4Ixb0--245" value="<p style="font-size: 16px;">1.
